{"id":"2001.06945","submitter":"Yong Xu","authors":"Bin Pei, Yuzuru Inahama and Yong Xu","title":"Averaging Principles for Mixed Fast-Slow Systems Driven by Fractional\n  Brownian Motion","comments":"23 pages accepted by Kyoto Journal of Mathematics","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We focus on fast-slow systems involving both fractional Brownian motion (fBm)\nand standard Brownian motion (Bm). The integral with respect to Bm is the\nstandard Ito integral, and the integral with respect to fBm is the generalised\nRiemann-Stieltjes integral using the tools of fractional calculus. An averaging\nprinciple in which the fast-varying diffusion process of the fast-slow systems\nacts as a noise to be averaged out in the limit is established. It is shown\nthat the slow process has a limit in the mean square sense, which is\ncharacterized by the solution of stochastic differential equations driven by\nfBm whose coefficients are averaged with respect to the stationary measure of\nthe fast-varying diffusion. The implication is that one can ignore the complex\noriginal systems and concentrate on the averaged systems instead. This\naveraging principle paves the way for reduction of computational complexity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 20 Jan 2020 02:31:17 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 17 Jun 2020 07:08:41 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 13 Oct 2020 13:06:18 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 3 Nov 2021 06:34:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-11-04"}
