{"id":"2001.07033","submitter":"Linglong Yuan","authors":"Linglong Yuan","title":"Kingman's model with random mutation probabilities: convergence and\n  condensation I","comments":"25 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  For a one-locus haploid infinite population with discrete generations, the\ncelebrated Kingman's model describes the evolution of fitness distributions\nunder the competition of selection and mutation, with a constant mutation\nprobability. Letting mutation probabilities vary on generations reflects the\ninfluence of a random environment. This paper generalises Kingman's model by\nusing a sequence of i.i.d. random mutation probabilities. For any distribution\nof the sequence, the weak convergence of fitness distributions to the globally\nstable equilibrium for any initial fitness distribution is proved. We define\nthe condensation of the random model as that almost surely a positive\nproportion of the population travels to and condensates on the largest fitness\nvalue. The condensation may occur when selection is more favoured than\nmutation. A criterion is given to tell whether the condensation occurs or not.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 20 Jan 2020 09:47:18 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 31 May 2021 16:28:57 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-06-01"}
